    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/wkP5y.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 464475,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 868010,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/868010/josh-liptzin",
                "reputation": 794,
                "display_name": "Josh Liptzin",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1393370170,
            "creation_date": 1393370170,
            "body": "<p>You'd have to first serialize it (JSON format is probably easiest) and then deserialize it in javascript to be able to use it as an array.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22028331,
            "question_id": 22028290
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6442a4c51178c5953da42ce20f5c226f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 59461,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 177920,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/177920/madbreaks",
                "reputation": 19589,
                "display_name": "Madbreaks",
                "accept_rate": 77
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1393371694,
            "creation_date": 1393370159,
            "body": "<p>Yes, you'll need to convert the array to JSON first though, then have your JavaScript function parse that JSON.  At that point it can work with it as a standard JS array (because at that point, it is).<\/p>\n\n<p><em><strong>EDIT<\/em><\/strong> - I did not mean to imply that <code>JSON<\/code> is absolutely required, nor that it is the only possible solution. It's simply an option, and in my opinion probably the best and easiest for what you're trying to accomplish.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 22028327,
            "question_id": 22028290,
            "last_edit_date": 1393371694
        }
    ],
